    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-08-27T12:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-08-27T12:29:00-05:00" n="141"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d141">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/481</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Petrograd</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-08-27T21:00:00+03:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 27, 1917, 9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 30, 7.30 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1673. Your 1648 of the 24th received to-day and forwarded Moscow.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d141fn1">Transmitting the President’s telegram of Aug. 24, <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_177">p. 177</ref>.</note>
                    Think President’s salutation opportune, concise, remarkably well expressed.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NNV1">Nekrasov</persName> just left Embassy, says
                        <persName corresp="#p_TMI1">Tereshchenko</persName> who is in Moscow
                    telephoned that <persName corresp="#p_KGLG1">Kornilov</persName> spoke to-day
                    very satisfactorily, well received, and will have good effect throughout
                    country, removing anticipations of difference between <persName
                        corresp="#p_KGLG1">Kornilov</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_KAF1"
                        >Kerensky</persName>, claims he, <persName corresp="#p_KAF1"
                        >Kerensky</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_TMI1">Tereshchenko</persName>
                    had known since the 23d that <persName corresp="#p_KGLG1">Kornilov</persName>
                    loyal to Provisional Government. Says Cadets resolved last night to support
                    Provisional Government and conference will adjourn evening 28th after forty
                    speeches limited ten minutes each. Says furthermore Assistant Minister of War
                    told him confidentially wished Bolsheviks had made outbreak as was thoroughly
                    prepared therefor. Very quiet here.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
